In short, for all pairs {{2110.13883_FO0269||FO}} for which {{2110.13883_FO0270||FO}}, we approximate their local geodesic distance via their Euclidian distance normalized by a constant factor. The normalization factor ensures that the normalized distances are always smaller than {{2110.13883_FO0271||FO}}, i.e. the smallest non-zero value that {{2110.13883_FO0272||FO}} can attain. It consists of {{2110.13883_FO0273||FO}}, the maximum {{2110.13883_FO0274||FO}}-norm between any two pairs {{2110.13883_FO0275||FO}}, the number of trees {{2110.13883_FO0276||FO}} and a small constant {{2110.13883_FO0277||FO}}.